{% navigation_tag "equilibria"  "Equilibria" %}
<div style="page-break-inside: avoid"><h4>Equilibria</h4>

<p>Recall that the equilibrium point of a discrete dynamical system is a constant solution to a dynamical system.  In other words, an equilibrium solution is a numerical value which when entered 
as an initial condition creates a trajectory in which every entry is identical to the initial condition, i.e. the solution will be
\[
 \{x_0, x_0, x_0, \ldots \}.
\]
Since all points will be the same, to find these values we set $x_n=x_{n+1}=E$ in the system and solve for $E$.</p></div>

<p>Calculate the equilibrium point(s) for each of the following:</p>
<ol>
  <li class="smallspacebelow">$x_{n+1} -x_n = \frac{1}{2}x_n$</li>
  <li class="smallspacebelow">$x_{n+1} = \frac{1}{2}x_n$</li>
  <li class="smallspacebelow">$x_{n+1} = 2 x_n -10$</li>
  <li class="smallspacebelow">$x_{n+1} -x_n = 2x_n(1-x_n)$</li>
  <li class="smallspacebelow">$x_{n+1} = 2x_n(1-x_n)$</li>
</ol>

<p class="question medspacebelow">Suppose you have a dynamical system with two parameters $c$ and $d$ of the form
